      "content": "Great question! If there's a disagreement or missing paperwork, the escrow account can indeed become a bit of a stalemate. However, the third party holding the funds, whether it's a lawyer or an escrow company, has the responsibility to resolve these issues before releasing the money. They act as a neutral party to ensure that both the buyer and seller are satisfied with the terms of the sale. If there's a dispute, the third party may request additional documentation or clarification from both parties. In some cases, they might even suggest mediation to help resolve the disagreement. The goal is to ensure that all conditions are met and that both parties are in agreement before the funds are released. It's not indefinite, but it can take some time to resolve any issues that arise.",
